body:
@granthenke thanks again for your hard work on this. I also tested thoroughly, and works perfectly. 

I extended this in #2615 to support renaming the consumer group as part of the migration. 

I'm torn on whether this should land in core... it's useful to have here in a PR so that others can find/re-use, but this code will rarely get used outside of upgrading. That said, it is extremely useful when dealing with non-Java clients as most of those don't support `dual.commit`.

@hachikuji Thanks for reviewing the patch. Yes I have considered the idea of replacing `unsent` with some concurrent collection as you mentioned. But code using `synchronized(unsent)` seems simpler than that approach. For example, we need to have a lock while iterating over `unsent` (e.g. `pendingRequestCount()`, `checkDisconnects()`) and `ConcurrentLinkedQueue` does not provide an easy way to do that. Maybe it is possible to argue that these methods can still return acceptable results even if the items in the unsent can be changed while we iterate over it, but we would have to go through all the scenarios to prove it and the solution will be error prone.

Do  you think there is clear performance advantage of using concurrent collection instead of using `synchronized(unsent)`. If not, maybe we can choose the solution that is simpler and less error prone?

Also, note that the performance of having this extra synchronzie(unset) will not be worse than current implementation of using a global lock everywhere.
